\f0\fs24 \cf0 She found them in the bottom of the suitcase, tucked beneath a wool sweater she had not worn in years. A bundle of letters, held together with a rubber band that snapped when she pulled it.\
\
They were all addressed to her mother. None of them had been sent.\
\
Lena sat on the edge of the narrow hotel bed and unfolded the oldest one, its creases soft as cloth. The handwriting was rounder than hers was now, younger, still trying to impress.\
\
\f1\i Dear Mama,\
\
I know you think I left because I was angry. I wasn\'92t angry. I was terrified. The village was getting smaller every day and I could feel myself shrinking with it. I needed to go somewhere I could be no one for a while, so that I could figure out who I was meant to be. I am sorry I did not say this to your face. I am sorry for a great many things I cannot yet name.\
\f0\i0 \
\
She folded the letter along its original lines and placed it on the pillow. There were eleven more. She was not ready for them\'97not tonight\'97but she left them on the bedside table where she could see them, their edges curling upward like small hands reaching.}